    "background": "No background available.",
    "resolution_criteria": "This is a market about inflation over the 12 month period ending December 2024 before seasonal adjustment as reported by the Bureau of Labor Statistics.\n\nThis market will resolve to “Yes” if the index increased by 2.6 percent or less over the 12 month period ending December 2024 and “No“ otherwise.\n\nThe resolution source for this market will be the BLS December 2024 Consumer Price Index report (https://www.bls.gov/bls/news-release/cpi.htm), currently scheduled to be released on January 15, 2025, at 8:30 AM ET. Resolution of this market will take place upon release of the aforementioned data.\n\n----\n\nThe Consumer Price Index (CPI) is a measure of the average change over time in the prices paid by urban consumers for a market basket of consumer goods and services.\n\nNote: the resolution source for this market will be the official monthly BLS CPI news release which reports inflation over 12 month periods to only one decimal point (e.g. 2.9%). Thus, this is the level of precision that will be used when resolving the market.",
    "outcome": "No",
    "explanation": "## Executive Summary\nThe US annual inflation for December 2024 did not fall to 2.6% or less, resolving the question to 'No'. Inflationary pressures proved more persistent than anticipated in early 2024. Despite some cooling, sectors like housing and services kept the core CPI elevated. By the release date on January 15, 2025, the CPI data confirmed that annual inflation remained above the 2.6% threshold.\n\n## Timeline Of Key Events\n- Early to Mid 2024: Initial optimism that inflation would reach 2.6% or lower by year-end. [art_general_20240619_015_e771613d]\n- 2024-12-19: Market sentiment shifted due to persistent economic data indicating stickier inflation. [art_general_20250114_025_075f08ae]\n- 2024-12-23: Another significant turning point, where expectations for lower inflation diminished. [art_general_20250114_057_d3d1f464]\n- 2025-01-04: Further realization that core inflation components were not dropping as expected. [art_general_20250211_009_e8f233e0]\n- 2025-01-09: Late expectations adjusted prior to the CPI release, solidifying the view that inflation would miss the 2.6% target. [art_finance_20250317_009_4d66aa60]\n- 2025-01-15: Final CPI report released for December 2024, confirming annual inflation exceeded 2.6%. [art_finance_20260316_017_56401c6b]\n\n## Causal Chain Analysis\nThe outcome was driven by a combination of persistent structural factors. Resilient consumer demand and a tight labor market led to higher-than-expected wage growth, which caused services inflation to remain elevated. This persistent services inflation, combined with stubborn housing costs, meant that the broader CPI could not cool enough. As a result, when the December CPI data was released, the annual inflation rate was firmly above the 2.6% threshold.\n\n## Countervailing Factors\nSome factors pushed towards lower inflation, such as easing supply chain pressures and lower goods prices earlier in the year. However, these were overwhelmed by the persistent inflation in services and housing.\n\n## Event Candidate Inventory\n* E1: Services inflation remains sticky\n  * Date: Mid to late 2024\n  * Causally relevant: Prevented the overall CPI from falling to target.\n  * Source: [art_general_20241228_018_0f28f53b]\n* E2: December CPI Release\n  * Date: 2025-01-15\n  * Causally relevant: The final data point that resolved the question.\n  * Source: [art_finance_20260316_017_56401c6b]\n\n## Evidence Mapping Table\n| Claim/Event | Article IDs | Date Support | Confidence (0-1) | Notes |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Inflation above 2.6% | art_finance_20260316_017_56401c6b | 2025-01-15 | 1.0 | Final release |\n| Persistent services inflation | art_general_20241228_018_0f28f53b | Late 2024 | 0.9 | Underlying cause |\n\n## Uncertainties And Alternative Paths\nIf housing costs had cooled faster or if the labor market had weakened significantly, inflation might have dropped to 2.6% or below.\n",
